  "prompt": "What are some of the funniest movies you've ever seen?",
  "response": "Comedy is quite subjective, but there are several movies widely regarded as some of the funniest in cinema. Here are a few that often come up in discussions:\n\n1. **\"Airplane!\" (1980)** - Known for its slapstick humor, wordplay, and visual gags, this parody of the disaster film genre is a classic.\n\n2. **\"Monty Python and the Holy Grail\" (1975)** - This British comedy from the Monty Python crew offers a unique and absurd take on the Arthurian legend.\n\n3. **\"Anchorman: The Legend of Ron Burgundy\" (2004)** - Will Ferrell stars as a clueless news anchor in this satirical look at 1970s newsrooms.\n\n4. **\"The Big Lebowski\" (1998)** - A Coen Brothers film featuring the unforgettable character \"The Dude,\" with a quirky plot and memorable lines.\n\n5. **\"Bridesmaids\" (2011)** - A hit comedy that blends crude humor with heartfelt moments, focusing on friendship and wedding chaos.\n\n6. **\"Superbad\" (2007)** - A coming-of-age comedy that follows two high school friends on an epic night before graduation.\n\n7. **\"Step Brothers\" (2008)** - Will Ferrell and John C. Reilly team up as immature stepbrothers in this over-the-top comedy.\n\n8. **\"Borat\" (2006)** - Sacha Baron Cohen\u2019s mockumentary follows the antics of a fictitious Kazakh journalist as he travels across the United States.\n\n9. **\"Caddyshack\" (1980)** - A madcap comedy set on a golf course, featuring a cast of eccentric characters including Bill Murray and Chevy Chase.\n\n10. **\"Ghostbusters\" (1984)** - A supernatural comedy about a team of parapsychologists who start a ghost-catching business in New York City.\n\nThese films offer a range of comedic styles, from slapstick and satire to situational and character-driven humor, making them beloved by many.",
